const _astro_dataLayerContent = [["Map",1,2,9,10,42,43],"meta::meta",["Map",3,4,5,6,7,8],"astro-version","5.1.3","content-config-digest","9d54a51fe2b457d5","astro-config-digest","{\"root\":{},\"srcDir\":{},\"publicDir\":{},\"outDir\":{},\"cacheDir\":{},\"site\":\"https://www.timeaton.dev/\",\"compressHTML\":true,\"base\":\"/\",\"trailingSlash\":\"ignore\",\"output\":\"static\",\"scopedStyleStrategy\":\"attribute\",\"build\":{\"format\":\"directory\",\"client\":{},\"server\":{},\"assets\":\"_astro\",\"serverEntry\":\"entry.mjs\",\"redirects\":true,\"inlineStylesheets\":\"auto\",\"concurrency\":1},\"server\":{\"open\":false,\"host\":false,\"port\":4321,\"streaming\":true},\"redirects\":{},\"image\":{\"endpoint\":{\"route\":\"/_image\"},\"service\":{\"entrypoint\":\"astro/assets/services/sharp\",\"config\":{}},\"domains\":[],\"remotePatterns\":[]},\"devToolbar\":{\"enabled\":true},\"markdown\":{\"syntaxHighlight\":\"shiki\",\"shikiConfig\":{\"langs\":[],\"langAlias\":{},\"theme\":\"material-theme-darker\",\"themes\":{},\"wrap\":false,\"transformers\":[]},\"remarkPlugins\":[],\"rehypePlugins\":[],\"remarkRehype\":{},\"gfm\":true,\"smartypants\":true},\"security\":{\"checkOrigin\":true},\"env\":{\"schema\":{},\"validateSecrets\":false},\"experimental\":{\"clientPrerender\":false,\"contentIntellisense\":false,\"responsiveImages\":false},\"legacy\":{\"collections\":false}}","finds",["Map",11,12,23,24,33,34],"cyber-city",{id:11,data:13,filePath:20,digest:21,rendered:22},{title:14,link:15,description:16,type:17,publicationDate:18,"public":19},"How Akira Created The Most Iconic CyberPunk City","https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cMx5ajcWnMU","","video",["Date","2025-01-01T00:00:00.000Z"],true,"src/content/finds/cyber-city.md","b3c26edf44d8a810",{html:16},"fonts-web-sustainable",{id:23,data:25,filePath:30,digest:31,rendered:32},{title:26,link:27,description:16,type:28,publicationDate:29,"public":19},"How to load web fonts for the best page load performance","https://the-sustainable.dev/how-to-load-web-fonts-for-the-best-page-load-performance/","article",["Date","2024-12-03T00:00:00.000Z"],"src/content/finds/fonts-web-sustainable.md","34253bccd8d41747",{html:16},"lego-panels",{id:33,data:35,filePath:39,digest:40,rendered:41},{title:36,link:37,description:16,type:28,publicationDate:38,"public":19},"The UX of LEGO Interface Panels","https://interactionmagic.com/UX-LEGO-Interfaces/",["Date","2024-12-20T00:00:00.000Z"],"src/content/finds/lego-panels.md","7a312d119546db49",{html:16},"posts",["Map",44,45,62,63,78,79,94,95,110,111],"french-dentist",{id:44,data:46,body:52,filePath:53,digest:54,rendered:55},{title:47,slug:44,author:48,description:49,category:50,publicationDate:51,"public":19},"The French Dentist Incident","Glyptodon","A tale of miscommunication, mime, and dental hygiene in Paris","life",["Date","2025-01-04T00:00:00.000Z"],"I've always believed that the true measure of a country's civilization isn't its art museums or opera houses, but rather its dental practices. In Paris, this theory was put to the test when I found myself in the chair of Dr. Laurent, a man whose commitment to causing discomfort rivaled that of medieval torturers.\n\n\"Zees will only hurt a leetle,\" he said, brandishing what appeared to be a repurposed car jack. I noticed his diploma was written in crayon, but by then it was too late to run.\n\nThe waiting room had been my first clue. Instead of the usual magazines, there were only copies of Victor Hugo's Les Misérables, presumably to remind patients that things could always be worse. A fish tank contained what I'm certain was a piranha, though the receptionist insisted it was a \"friendly goldfish with an attitude.\"","src/content/posts/french-dentist.md","77f94b0ea071e393",{html:56,metadata:57},"<p>I’ve always believed that the true measure of a country’s civilization isn’t its art museums or opera houses, but rather its dental practices. In Paris, this theory was put to the test when I found myself in the chair of Dr. Laurent, a man whose commitment to causing discomfort rivaled that of medieval torturers.</p>\n<p>“Zees will only hurt a leetle,” he said, brandishing what appeared to be a repurposed car jack. I noticed his diploma was written in crayon, but by then it was too late to run.</p>\n<p>The waiting room had been my first clue. Instead of the usual magazines, there were only copies of Victor Hugo’s Les Misérables, presumably to remind patients that things could always be worse. A fish tank contained what I’m certain was a piranha, though the receptionist insisted it was a “friendly goldfish with an attitude.”</p>",{headings:58,imagePaths:59,frontmatter:60},[],[],{title:47,slug:44,description:49,publicationDate:61,category:50,"public":19,author:48},["Date","2025-01-04T00:00:00.000Z"],"airport-security",{id:62,data:64,body:68,filePath:69,digest:70,rendered:71},{title:65,slug:62,author:48,description:66,category:50,publicationDate:67,"public":19},"Adventures in Airport Security","That time I tried to explain why I had a rubber chicken in my carry-on",["Date","2025-01-03T00:00:00.000Z"],"The TSA agent held up my carry-on bag, which contained what I thought was a perfectly reasonable art installation: three rubber ducks, a vintage toaster, and a copy of Richard Nixon's autobiography connected by yarn. \"Sir,\" she said with the weary tone of someone who's seen everything but still manages to be surprised, \"what exactly is this?\"\n\n\"It's art,\" I explained, as if that would clarify everything. \"The ducks represent capitalism, the toaster is a metaphor for political burnout, and the yarn... well, the yarn ties it all together.\" She looked at me the way my father used to when I told him I wanted to be a writer.\n\nBehind me, a businessman in an expensive suit cleared his throat loudly, as if to say, \"Some of us have planes to catch and don't have time for this postmodern nonsense.\"","src/content/posts/airport-security.md","9f600b3f9adda2dd",{html:72,metadata:73},"<p>The TSA agent held up my carry-on bag, which contained what I thought was a perfectly reasonable art installation: three rubber ducks, a vintage toaster, and a copy of Richard Nixon’s autobiography connected by yarn. “Sir,” she said with the weary tone of someone who’s seen everything but still manages to be surprised, “what exactly is this?”</p>\n<p>“It’s art,” I explained, as if that would clarify everything. “The ducks represent capitalism, the toaster is a metaphor for political burnout, and the yarn… well, the yarn ties it all together.” She looked at me the way my father used to when I told him I wanted to be a writer.</p>\n<p>Behind me, a businessman in an expensive suit cleared his throat loudly, as if to say, “Some of us have planes to catch and don’t have time for this postmodern nonsense.”</p>",{headings:74,imagePaths:75,frontmatter:76},[],[],{title:65,slug:62,description:66,publicationDate:77,category:50,"public":19,author:48},["Date","2025-01-03T00:00:00.000Z"],"japanese-toilet",{id:78,data:80,body:84,filePath:85,digest:86,rendered:87},{title:81,slug:78,author:48,description:82,category:50,publicationDate:83,"public":19},"The High-Tech Toilet Incident","My first encounter with a Japanese smart toilet, and how I accidentally became a viral sensation",["Date","2025-01-02T00:00:00.000Z"],"The toilet in my Tokyo hotel room had more buttons than a space shuttle. There was a control panel on the side with symbols that looked like hieroglyphics designed by a committee of drunk robots. One button had what appeared to be a musical note being struck by lightning – was this for emergency karaoke situations?\n\nMy sister Amy would have just pressed every button until something happened, but I took the scholarly approach and pulled out Google Translate. Unfortunately, the app translated \"gentle cleansing spray\" as \"water dragon awakening ceremony,\" which really didn't help my anxiety.\n\nThe breaking point came when I accidentally pressed what I thought was the flush button, only to be serenaded by bird sounds while warm air blasted from unexpected directions. Somewhere in the great beyond, my father was laughing.","src/content/posts/japanese-toilet.md","daff93b0f4fd1d4b",{html:88,metadata:89},"<p>The toilet in my Tokyo hotel room had more buttons than a space shuttle. There was a control panel on the side with symbols that looked like hieroglyphics designed by a committee of drunk robots. One button had what appeared to be a musical note being struck by lightning – was this for emergency karaoke situations?</p>\n<p>My sister Amy would have just pressed every button until something happened, but I took the scholarly approach and pulled out Google Translate. Unfortunately, the app translated “gentle cleansing spray” as “water dragon awakening ceremony,” which really didn’t help my anxiety.</p>\n<p>The breaking point came when I accidentally pressed what I thought was the flush button, only to be serenaded by bird sounds while warm air blasted from unexpected directions. Somewhere in the great beyond, my father was laughing.</p>",{headings:90,imagePaths:91,frontmatter:92},[],[],{title:81,slug:78,description:82,publicationDate:93,category:50,"public":19,author:48},["Date","2025-01-02T00:00:00.000Z"],"family-dinner",{id:94,data:96,body:100,filePath:101,digest:102,rendered:103},{title:97,slug:94,author:48,description:98,category:50,publicationDate:99,"public":19},"The Great Family Dinner Debacle","How I managed to offend three generations with one mistranslated compliment",["Date","2025-01-01T00:00:00.000Z"],"My mother approached Thanksgiving dinner the way some people approach defusing bombs: with a mixture of precision, terror, and the persistent feeling that everything could explode at any moment. The turkey was less a meal than a yearly referendum on our family's stability.\n\n\"The secret,\" she would say, consulting a recipe card that had been handled so many times it resembled ancient papyrus, \"is to treat the bird like it's plotting against you.\" This explained why she would sometimes stand in the kitchen at 3 AM, staring suspiciously at the refrigerator.\n\nMy sister Lisa once suggested we try tofurkey instead. Mom responded by clutching her pearls so hard they nearly turned to diamonds. Dad, ever the diplomat, suggested we have both, not realizing he had just doubled the potential for disaster.","src/content/posts/family-dinner.md","c8ba84162e0060b8",{html:104,metadata:105},"<p>My mother approached Thanksgiving dinner the way some people approach defusing bombs: with a mixture of precision, terror, and the persistent feeling that everything could explode at any moment. The turkey was less a meal than a yearly referendum on our family’s stability.</p>\n<p>“The secret,” she would say, consulting a recipe card that had been handled so many times it resembled ancient papyrus, “is to treat the bird like it’s plotting against you.” This explained why she would sometimes stand in the kitchen at 3 AM, staring suspiciously at the refrigerator.</p>\n<p>My sister Lisa once suggested we try tofurkey instead. Mom responded by clutching her pearls so hard they nearly turned to diamonds. Dad, ever the diplomat, suggested we have both, not realizing he had just doubled the potential for disaster.</p>",{headings:106,imagePaths:107,frontmatter:108},[],[],{title:97,slug:94,description:98,publicationDate:109,category:50,"public":19,author:48},["Date","2025-01-01T00:00:00.000Z"],"language-class",{id:110,data:112,body:116,filePath:117,digest:118,rendered:119},{title:113,slug:110,author:48,description:114,category:50,publicationDate:115,"public":19},"Lost in Translation: My German Language Misadventures","How I accidentally told my language teacher I was a pregnant helicopter, and other linguistic failures",["Date","2025-01-05T00:00:00.000Z"],"The problem with learning German is that one wrong syllable can transform you from a polite tourist into someone accidentally declaring war on Switzerland. My language teacher, Frau Schmidt, had the patience of a saint and the expression of someone watching a car crash in slow motion.\n\n\"Ich bin ein Hubschrauber,\" I announced proudly to the class, thinking I was saying \"I am helpful.\" Instead, I had declared myself to be a helicopter. Frau Schmidt's eye began to twitch when I then attempted to conjugate myself into the past tense, essentially telling the class I was a helicopter who was expecting twins.\n\nThe other students, mostly young professionals hoping to work in Berlin, maintained straight faces with the kind of discipline that would impress a Royal Guard. Only Klaus, an elderly man taking the class \"to keep his mind sharp,\" would occasionally snort into his coffee when I spoke.","src/content/posts/language-class.md","4924c45a0564a0b2",{html:120,metadata:121},"<p>The problem with learning German is that one wrong syllable can transform you from a polite tourist into someone accidentally declaring war on Switzerland. My language teacher, Frau Schmidt, had the patience of a saint and the expression of someone watching a car crash in slow motion.</p>\n<p>“Ich bin ein Hubschrauber,” I announced proudly to the class, thinking I was saying “I am helpful.” Instead, I had declared myself to be a helicopter. Frau Schmidt’s eye began to twitch when I then attempted to conjugate myself into the past tense, essentially telling the class I was a helicopter who was expecting twins.</p>\n<p>The other students, mostly young professionals hoping to work in Berlin, maintained straight faces with the kind of discipline that would impress a Royal Guard. Only Klaus, an elderly man taking the class “to keep his mind sharp,” would occasionally snort into his coffee when I spoke.</p>",{headings:122,imagePaths:123,frontmatter:124},[],[],{title:113,slug:110,description:114,publicationDate:125,category:50,"public":19,author:48},["Date","2025-01-05T00:00:00.000Z"]];

